[1] Norovirus, students - USA (Pennsylvania)
Date: Thu 25 Mar 2004
From: Angela Lee <finchley@qis.net>
Source: Times/Allegheny Times, Thu 25 Mar 2004 [edited]

USA: Suspected Norovirus Outbreak Closes Cornell School in Coraopolis
--------------------------------------------------
[A schoolbus] driver said he has never seen anything like it in the 30
years he's transported students to the Cornell Educational Center in
Coraopolis. But the stomach illness that has plagued students, teachers,
and staff at the school since Thursday [18 Mar 2004] has continued to
spread rapidly, causing administrators to dismiss all of the district's 800
students early Tuesday [23 Mar 2004] and close the school for the remainder
of the week. All meetings and extracurricular activities also have been
postponed. Classes are scheduled to resume Mon 29 Mar 2004. The cause of
the illness has not been identified officially, but the Allegheny County
Health Department suspects it might be a consequence of norovirus infection.
Superintendent Dennis Johnson said the decision to close the school was
made after 80 elementary and 55 high school students did not report to
class on Tuesday. An additional 11 students were sent home sick in the 2
hours that school was in session. "It was in the best interest and safety
of our students and staff to dismiss early (Tuesday)," Johnson said.
"Students were literally getting sick while taking tests." The district was
in the midst of the Pennsylvania System of School Assessment tests, which
will be postponed until further notice. Johnson said he has been in contact
with the Pennsylvania Department of Education about the situation.
"This is definitely rare and a very strange situation," said Bethany
Yenner, spokeswoman for the department. "This isn't something you typically
see."
The illness began appearing Thursday among elementary students. Elementary
music teacher Martha Karipin said a kindergarten student was sick in her
classroom during the school day on Thursday. Many other students became
sick later that evening while attending the school's science fair. The
district dismissed all students early on Friday after nearly 80 elementary
students became sick. Since Friday, the illness has spread to junior and
senior high students as well as teachers and staff. Principal Erv
Weischedel has been sick since Monday, and the building's maintenance
director called in sick Tuesday, Johnson said. An additional 10 staff
members did not report Tuesday, and others were ill over the weekend.
Johnson said the district's maintenance staff will spend the next 3 days
disinfecting the school, checking the ventilation system and changing air
filters. The business manager is also looking into hiring a professional
cleaning firm, similar to those hired by hospitals.
Dave Zazac, spokesman for the Allegheny County Health Department, said the
illness has symptoms similar to those in a norovirus outbreak, including
nausea, vomiting, diarrhea and stomach cramps. Some also suffer a low-grade
fever. Symptoms usually subside within 48 hours, but the person remains
contagious for three more days. He added that official confirmation cannot
happen until laboratory results are received from the state Department of
Health. The results are expected to be returned by Friday [26 Mar 2004].
Meanwhile, the department is looking to collect more biological samples
from students and adults infected by the virus. It is also monitoring the
possibility of secondary infections, or those who have become sick after
coming in contact with a previously infected person or contaminated
surface, Zazac said. For additional information and announcements, parents
can log on to the district's Web site at <http://www.cornell.k12.pa.us>.
"We were hoping this was slowly but surely going away, but it has gotten
worse," Johnson said. The Allegheny County Health Department and the
Centers for Disease Control suggest the following methods to help prevent
the stomach virus affecting the Cornell School District from spreading:
Frequently wash your hands, especially after toilet visits and before
eating or preparing food; carefully wash fruits and vegetables before
eating them; thoroughly clean and disinfect contaminated surfaces
immediately after an episode of illness by using a bleach-based household
cleaner.
[Byline: Pete Sabella]
--
Angela Lee
<finchley@qis.net>
