[2] Norovirus, hotel - USA (Nevada)
Date: Thu 25 Mar 2004
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <arodriguezm@SaludFMV.org>
Source: Clark County Health District, Nevada, Norovirus - Public Health
Update #2, Mon 22 Mar 2004 [edited]
<http://www.cchd.org/download/news/032204.pdf>

USA: Norovirus Outbreak at the California Hotel and Casino in Las Vegas
---------------------------------------------------
The Clark County Health District today [Mon 22 Mar 2004] issued updated
totals for the number of gastrointestinal illness complaints pertaining to
a norovirus outbreak associated with the California Hotel and Casino in
Downtown Las Vegas. A team of communicable disease specialists from the
U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention arrived in Las Vegas late
last week to assist the health district with its investigation into this
outbreak.
The health district is compiling the number of gastrointestinal illness
complaints from several sources: Boyd Gaming (corporate owner of the
California Hotel) security reports forwarded to the health district by the
company, direct public reports to the health district, hospital reports and
doctor's office reports. The numbers represent people who visited or stayed
at the California Hotel after 3 Dec 2003, and complained of becoming ill
with vomiting and/or diarrhea either during or immediately following their
visit.
Total Cases
------------
Illness Onset / Health District Composite / Boyd Security Subset /
03-12/03/2003 / 1475 / 346 /
Breakdown by Month
------------------
Illness Onset / Health District Composite / Boyd Security Subset /
Dec 2003 / 178 / 39 /
Jan 2004 / 412 / 73 /
Feb 2004 / 616 / 121 /
Mar 2004 (partial) / 269 / 113 /
Breakdown by Week (updated)
---------------------------
Illness Onset / Health District Composite / Boyd Security Subset /
27 Feb -4 Mar / 173 / 48 /
5-12 Mar / 103 / 38 /
13-19 Mar / 50 / 33 /
The norovirus outbreak associated with the California Hotel has peaked and
declined several times. The Clark County Health District Office of
Epidemiology will classify the current outbreak as over when a sustained
decline to baseline levels (an average of 2-3 illness complaints per week)
has been observed for a period of one month (the amount of time noroviruses
can survive on environmental surfaces).
Late last week, the health district received test results that indicated
the presence of norovirus in the stool of 3 ill people who recently stayed
or visited the California Hotel. 2 of the 3 samples were tested at the
Hawaii State Public Health Laboratory; one sample was tested at the Nevada
State Public Health Laboratory.
The health district reminds guests of any hotel to promptly report
incidents of illness to the hotel housekeeping or general staff. Areas
affected by vomiting and/or diarrhea must be properly cleaned and
disinfected to protect others from getting ill. Additionally, the health
district reminds ill persons they are considered infectious until 3 days
after their symptoms have resolved. Appropriate sanitation and personal
hygiene should be observed even after an ill person begins to feel better.
Additional information on noroviruses is available on the health district
web site at <http://www.cchd.org/download/epi/norovirus.pdf>
and on the CDC web site at
<http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/dvrd/revb/gastro/norovirus.htm.
--
Dr.Alfonso J. Rodriguez, M.D.
<arodriguezm@saludfmv.org>
