[3] Norovirus, school - Portugal
Date: Thu 25 Mar 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Eurosurveillance Weekly, Volume 8, Issue 13, Thu 25 Mar 2004 [edited]
<http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ew/2004/040325.asp>

Portugal: Norovirus Outbreak in a School at Povoa do Varzim in the North
---------------------------------------------------
On 13 Jan 2004, the Autoridade de Saude (local health authority, LHA) of
Povoa do Varzim in the north of Portugal was informed that several children
and staff of a school had become ill with vomiting; diarrhoea was also
reported in some patients. The school had reopened on 5 Jan 2004 after the
usual Christmas holiday. The LHA visited the school on 14 Jan 2004, in
order to study and control the outbreak. This was the 1st time that a
norovirus outbreak in Portugal has been laboratory-confirmed, and the
timely intervention of the LHA allowed a thorough collection of data.
The school
----------
The school was a state school with 3 classes of children, each with its own
classroom and staff:
Group A (n=20): 17 children aged 3-5 years, 1 teacher and 2 auxiliary staff
members;
Group B (n=21): 20 children in grades 1 and 4 grades (ages 5-6 and 8-9
years) and one teacher;
Group C (n=17): 16 children in grades 2 and 3 (ages 6-7 and 7-8 years) and
one teacher; and
Group D (n=5): staff supporting all school groups: 3 auxiliary and 2
kitchen staff.
The LHA collected preliminary data and inspected the school premises. The
school's head teacher was interviewed and informed of the urgent need for
strict hygiene precautions and the exclusion from school of all symptomatic
children and staff until 48 hours after symptoms had gone.
Tap water and swab samples from 5 dishes were collected from the kitchen;
nasopharyngeal swabs and handwashes were collected from the 2 food
handlers. Faecal specimens from 3 cases were collected for analysis on 15
Jan 2004. The samples were tested at the Respiratory Virus and Enterovirus
Unit and the Food Microbiology Laboratory of the National Institute of Health.
Staff and the parents of all schoolchildren were interviewed (20 and 21 Jan
2004) using a structured questionnaire; questions about family members
(household contacts) were included. Those interviewed were asked to report
vomiting and/or diarrhoea occurring after the date of interview, until the
end of January 2004. Data was also collected on the consumption of meals at
the school. All persons reporting vomiting and/or watery diarrhoea that
began after 1 Jan 2004 were classified as cases.
Microbiological study
---------------------
Norovirus was identified in 2 of the 3 stool samples collected on 15 Jan
2004, using a reverse transcriptase polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR)
technique: case 15, a 49-year-old teacher of Group B; and case 23, an
8-year-old boy from Group C. Norovirus strains were sent to the Health
Protection Agency Enteric Virus Unit in England for characterisation and
were identified as belonging to genogroup II and similar to currently
circulating Grimsby/1995/UK strains (GII-4).
Tap water, dishes, and the hands of the kitchen staff tested negative for
coliforms, indicator organisms, and pathogens. Very small amounts of
_Staphylococcus aureus_ (not producing enterotoxins A-E) were isolated from
the nasopharyngeal swabs of both food handlers.
[At this point the text is supplemented by a figure illustrating the
duration of vomiting and/or diarrhoea and date of onset among school
members and household contacts.]
Epidemiology
------------
31 cases, with illness onset between 2-18 Jan 2004, were identified.
Reported symptoms were vomiting (87 percent), abdominal pain (68 percent),
nausea (58 percent), watery diarrhoea (52 percent), low-grade fever (42
percent), and myalgia (23 percent). All 4 patients who did not report
vomiting, reported watery diarrhoea. Most patients reported that the
disease was mild; 11 patients sought medical treatment but none was
admitted to hospital. Symptoms lasted from 1 to 12 days.
The overall attack rate in the school was 33 percent (21/63), and was
higher among staff members (60 percent = 6/10) than among schoolchildren
(28 percent = 15/53) (p=0.059; one tailed Fisher exact test). Neither of
the 2 food handlers reported symptoms. There were no statistically
significant (p=0.566) differences between attack rates in groups A, B, and
C. The attack rate (5 percent = 10/194) among household contacts (excluding
school members) was lower (p<0.001) than that reported among school members.
Most students and staff consumed meals in the school throughout the whole
period of the study. The menu was the same for everyone each day.
Most school cases (16/21) occurred in the first week after the reopening of
the school (5-11 Jan 2004), while most of the cases reported among
household contacts (9/10) began in the following week (12-18 Jan 2004).
A more detailed analysis of the questionnaires revealed some interesting
findings: (1) the first 2 cases, with onset on 2 Jan, were father and son
(aged 4 years, Group A); on 5 Jan the boy attended school while still
symptomatic; his sister, asymptomatic (aged 6 years, Group B), also
attended school; (2) cases 5 and 21, with dates of onset on 8 Jan, were
brothers aged 5 and 8 years (Groups A, C); (3) household contacts who
became ill on 13 and 18 Jan were daughter and mother, living with the
cousin/nephew (case 14) whose illness onset was 9 Jan (Group B); an
asymptomatic brother was also part of Group B; (4) the teacher of Group C
became ill on 10 Jan (case 24); 5 family members living with her became ill
on 12, 14 and 15 Jan; (5) the household contact with a date of onset on 12
Jan (case 11) was the brother (age 1 year) of an asymptomatic girl (age 5
years) of Group A; (6) vomiting episodes occurred in the classrooms and in
communal areas, such as the canteen; vomit was cleaned by auxiliary staff;
(7) from Monday to Friday (the school week, from 5-22 Jan), cases in staff
and schoolchildren accounted for 50 days of symptoms of vomiting and/or
watery diarrhoea (children were excluded from school for 14 of those days;
but not a single day of exclusion was reported in staff.
Discussion
----------
It is not likely that the outbreak was foodborne or waterborne. The rapid
spread and high attack rate may be explained by the faecal-oral and
airborne viral transmission from fomites (1). Outbreaks in schools have
already been described (2), and the potential for spreading the disease by
vomiting has also been reported previously (2,3). Case 2, who became ill on
2 Jan 2004, was a primary case. We can exclude neither the hypothesis that
case 12 (onset on 5 Jan 2004) was a co-primary case nor that the
asymptomatic sister of case 2 might have played a role in introducing the
virus into the school community. The disease spread inside each group and
outward to household contacts. We do not know what role asymptomatic cases
may have played in the spread of the outbreak, although asymptomatic cases
have been reported to have helped spread outbreaks elsewhere (4). The
higher attack rate among staff members is likely to be a result of the
higher number of personal contacts (mostly with children) within the
school. The difficulty of controlling person-to-person spread has been
documented, especially if symptoms include vomiting (5). We were able to
identify in detail the days on which each patient had symptoms; [the data
suggest] an increased probability of transmission within the school and
family environments throughout most of the duration of the outbreak.
Nevertheless, we do not know whether very poor compliance with exclusion
from school, especially before the visit of the LHA, is likely to have
played a role in the spread of the disease.
References
-----------
(1) Chin J, ed. Epidemic viral gastroenteropathy. In: Control of
communicable diseases manual. 17th ed. Washington, DC: American Public
Health Association; 2000. p. 218-20.
(2)Marks PJ, Vipond IB, Regan FM, Wedgwood K, Fey RE, Caul EO. A school
outbreak of Norwalk-like virus: evidence for airborne transmission.
Epidemiol Infect 2003; 131: 727-36.
(3) Evans MR, Meldrum R, Lane W, Gardner D, Ribeiro CD, Gallimore CI, et
al. An outbreak of viral gastroenteritis following environmental
contamination at a concert hall. Epidemiol Infect 2002; 129: 355-60.
(4) Brumley D. Norwalk Virus. Presentation to Board of Public Health
Duxbury, Massachusetts. 20 March 2003. Published on the website of the town
of Duxbury, Massachusetts.
(<http://www.town.duxbury.ma.us/Public_Documents/DuxburyMA_Health/Norwalk
percent20Virus percent20Presentation.pdf>)
(5) Cowden JM. Winter vomiting. Infections due to Norwalk-like viruses are
underestimated. BMJ 2002; 324: 249-50.
(<http://bmj.bmjjournals.com/cgi/reprint/324/7332/249.pdf>)
[Byline: Luis Castro (<epd@crsp-norte.min-saude.pt>), Ana Isabel Cardoso,
Helena Rebelo-Andrade, Jim Gray, Margarida Saraiva, and Guilherme Goncalves]
